Qualitative1: I remember during one summer at primary school, year 4. I've always been a high achiever at school ever since I was young. Pupils were segregated based on their academic achievements during test, as such I was placed in the highest set (class) on the top table, the rest of the students on this table were  white/English. I remember having a particular discussion, unprovoked; a boy named Sam turned to me and said your skin is brown like poo. It was the first time I really felt different from others, I didn't kinow how to respond and began to cry. When the teacher asked what had happened I couldn't get myself to tell her, I knew that what he said was wrong but she (the teacher) was also white like him. I also knew that what he had said wasn't inaccurate, poo is brown, as am I, albeit a different shade. This idea would stick with me for a number of years and cause me to have an existential crisis in my mid teens. I'm also bengali, more often than not I am called a Pakistani.
Qualitative2: It was the first time I really felt different from others, I didn't kinow how to respond and began to cry. When the teacher asked what had happened I couldn't get myself to tell her, I knew that what he said was wrong but she (the teacher) was also white like him. I also knew that what he had said wasn't inaccurate, poo is brown, as am I, albeit a different shade. This idea would stick with me for a number of years and cause me to have an existential crisis in my mid teens. Being regarded as different all my life has led me to feeling desensitised. I know that I am different. But I'm too british to be bengali and too bengali to be british, so wherever I go, no label will accurately represent who I truly am - somewhere inbetween.
